    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>It's Time to Talk About Global Warming</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Robert Berkman letter says global warming should be public safety issue not political or ideological one</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Time to Connect the Dots'' mentions the split between environmentalists and right-wing talk shows over global warming's link to Hurricanes Katrina and Rita.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Time to Connect the Dots'' mentions the split between environmentalists and right-wing talk shows over global warming's link to Hurricanes Katrina and Rita.</p>
        <p>What I fail to understand is why global warming has come to be viewed as a political or ideological issue at all. If you are in a house where there's a strong burning smell and the air is getting smoky, the sane response is to acknowledge that there is a fire somewhere and do something about it -- no matter what one's political ideology might be.</p>
        <p>A warming planet, like a burning home, is a public safety issue, not an ideological one.</p>
        <p>Robert Berkman  Rochester, Sept. 28, 2005</p>
      </block>
